Step 1. Do we need a product term?

  • Run models with and without a product term
    • Compare using LR test
m1 <- glm(y ~ sensation4 + gender,
          family = poisson(link = "log"),
          data = jpa)
m2 <- glm(y ~ sensation4 + gender + sensation4*gender,
          family = poisson(link = "log"),
          data = jpa)
lrtest(m1, m2)

Step 2. Marginal effect

  • Thereâs not a single marginal effect (i.e., \(b_3\))
    • The marginal effect depends on the predictor(s)
    • It is conditional on the predictor(s)

modglm() inputs

  • modglm() function in modglm package
    • model = the model you want to use (m2 above)
    • vars = the variables in the model
      • Donât include the product term
      • Remember the model doesnât have to have a product term
    • data = the data used to estimate the model
    • type = type of interaction (i.e., the predictors)
      • cpd for continuous by continuous
      • fd for continuous by categorical
      • dd for categorical by categorical
    • hyps = values of predictors to get interaction effects for
      • Default is "means" of each variable
      • Can also select specific values of sensation4 and gender
        • e.g.: hyps = c(1, 2, 0)
          • 1 = intercept
          • 2 = sensation4 equal to 2 (sensation = 6)
          • 0 = gender equal to 0 (female)
ints<-modglm(model=m2, 
             vars=c("sensation4","gender"), 
             data=jpa, 
             type="fd", 
             hyps="means")

modglm() outputs

  • obints: data frame with values for each observation (case)
    • int.est = interaction estimate for that observation
    • hat = predicted outcome value
    • se.int.est = standard error of the interaction
    • t.val = \(t\)-statistic (i.e., estimate / standard error)
    • sig = whether the \(t\) statistic is significant (i.e., is there a significant interaction effect?)

    • t.val = \(t\)-statistic (i.e., estimate / standard error)

  • prop.sig = proportion of observations for whom the interaction is significant
    • Here, all of them
    • The instantaneous slopes are different between men and women for all observed values of sensation4
  • This is kind of similar to Johnson-Neyman approach to interactions

    • In this case, for all values of sensation4 in the sample

  • intsplot = plot of interaction effect (Y) vs predicted outcome value (X)
    • Points are colored by whether the interaction is significant
      • All observations show a significant interaction effect here
      • See McCabe et al.Â (2020), Figure 4 for an example where thatâs not true

Bootstrapping interaction effect

  • This is just one way to bootstrap
mean_int.est <- function(data, indices) {
    val <- data[indices,] 
    return(val$int.est)
} 
output <- boot(data=jpa_aug, 
               statistic=mean_int.est,

Step 3. Conditional effects

  • Simple slopes are conditional effects
  • Grab the coefficients from the model
b0_m2 <- coefficients(m2)[1] # intercept
b1_m2 <- coefficients(m2)[2] # sensation4
b2_m2 <- coefficients(m2)[3] # gender
b3_m2 <- coefficients(m2)[4] # product term
b0_m2
(Intercept) 
   0.464535 
b1_m2
sensation4 
 0.1031797 
b2_m2
   gender 
0.5553977 
b3_m2
sensation4:gender 
        0.2143403
  • Overall model equation (usual way)

\[\hat{\mu} = e^{0.465 + 0.103 (sensation4) + 0.555 (gender) + 0.214 (gender*sensation4)}\]

  • Overall model equation (simple slopes arrangement)

\[\hat{\mu} = e^{(\color{red}{0.465 + 0.555 gender} \color{black}{) + (}\color{blue}{0.103 + 0.214 gender}\color{black}{) sensation4}}\]

  • Conditional effect when gender = 0
    • \(\hat{\mu} = e^{(\color{red}{0.465}\color{black}{) + (}\color{blue}{0.103}\color{black}{) sensation4}}\)
      • RR = \(e^{\color{blue}{0.103}} = 1.109\)
      • For a 1 unit change in sensation4, the expected number of drinks for women increases by 1.109 times
      • For a 1 unit change in sensation4, the expected number of drinks for women increases by 10.9 percent
  • Conditional effect when gender = 1
    • \(\hat{\mu} = e^{(\color{red}{0.465 + 0.555}\color{black}{) + (}\color{blue}{0.103 + 0.214}\color{black}{) sensation4}} = e^{(\color{red}{1.02}\color{black}{) + (}\color{blue}{0.318}\color{black}{) sensation4}}\)
      • RR = \(e^{\color{blue}{0.318}} = 1.374\)
      • For a 1 unit change in sensation4, the expected number of drinks for men increases by 1.374 times
      • For a 1 unit change in sensation4, the expected number of drinks for men increases by 37.4 percent

Plots

  • You can get ggplot() to plot the simple slopes automatically or manually
    • The automatic version is quick and easy
    • The manual version is helpful if you want to plot some other function (e.g., the simple slopes for the model without the product term, as in the lecture)

Automatic version

  • X axis: x = sensation4
  • Y axis: y = y
  • group = as.factor(gender)
    • Everything it plots will be done separately for each gender
      • For example, lines it plots
    • as.factor() tells it to treat gender as a categorical variable (i.e., âfactorâ in R parlance) instead of a continuous variable that just happens to be 0 and 1
      • If you donât do this, some of the options donât work right because they only work for categorical variables
  • geom_point() adds the observe values
    • aes(color = as.factor(gender), shape = as.factor(gender)) makes the points different colors and different shapes depending on the value of gender
    • alpha = 0.3, size = 3 makes the points transparent and larger
  • geom_smooth() adds the lines
    • method = "glm", method.args = list(family = "poisson") tells it to use a Poisson GLM model for the line
    • linewidth = 2 makes the line thicker
    • se = FALSE removes the standard error bands
      • You can add these back, but the plot will be busier
    • aes(color = as.factor(gender)) makes the lines different colors depending on the value of gender
  • We actually did this above, but Iâll put it here again
ggplot(data = jpa, aes(x = sensation4, y = y, group = as.factor(gender))) +
    geom_point(aes(color = as.factor(gender), shape = as.factor(gender)),
               alpha = 0.3, size = 3) +
    geom_smooth(method = "glm", method.args = list(family = "poisson"), 
                linewidth = 2, se = FALSE,
                aes(color = as.factor(gender))) +
    theme(legend.position = "none")
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

Manual version

  • X axis: x = sensation4
  • Y axis: y = y
  • No group option: It still works if you include it, but it gives an error
  • geom_point() adds the observe values
    • aes(color = as.factor(gender), shape = as.factor(gender)) makes the points different colors and different shapes depending on the value of gender
    • alpha = 0.3, size = 3 makes the points transparent and larger
  • geom_function() adds the lines
    • fun = function(x) exp(b0_m2 + b1_m2*x) is the function youâd like to plot
      • The first one does the simple slope for gender = 0: \(e^{b_0 + b_1 X}\)
    • fun = function(x) exp((b0_m2 + b2_m2) + (b1_m2 + b3_m2)*x) is the second function
      • Simple slope for gender = 1: \(e^{(b_0 + b_2) + (b_1 + b_3) X}\)
    • linewidth = 2 makes the line thicker
    • I specified the colors for each line to match the points and the lines in the other figure
      • These are the hex code values for those teal and salmon colors
ggplot(data = jpa, aes(x = sensation4, y = y)) +
    geom_point(aes(color = as.factor(gender), shape = as.factor(gender)), 
               alpha = 0.3, size = 3) +
    geom_function(fun = function(x) exp(b0_m2 + b1_m2*x), 
                  linewidth = 2, color = "#F8766D") +
    geom_function(fun = function(x) exp((b0_m2 + b2_m2) + (b1_m2 + b3_m2)*x), 
                  linewidth = 2, color = "#00BFC4") +
    theme(legend.position = "none")

  • Again, you could use this latter method if you wanted to plot the simple slopes for a model with no product term (i.e., no product term that modifies the slope)
    • Just all the appropriate values and plug them in

Mediation

Equations

\(a\) path: \(\hat{M} = i_{MX} + aX\)

\(b\) and \(c'\) paths: \(\hat{Y} = i_{YXM} + bM + c'X\)

\(c\) path: \(\hat{Y} = i_{YX} + cX\)

  • Modify each equation as need to logistic regression, Poisson regression, etc.

Conditional indirect effect

\(X\) to \(M\)

xtom <- lm(sensation4 ~ gender, data = jpa)
coefficients(xtom)
(Intercept)      gender 
   1.242024   -0.118866 
xtom_i <- coefficients(xtom)[1]
names(xtom_i) <- NULL
xtom_a <- coefficients(xtom)[2]
names(xtom_a) <- NULL
  • Linear regression
    • \(a\) = \(-0.119\)

\(M\) to \(Y\)

mtoy <- glm(y ~ sensation4 + gender, data = jpa, family = poisson(link = "log"))
coefficients(mtoy)
(Intercept)  sensation4      gender 
  0.2545520   0.2608472   0.8394682 
mtoy_i <- coefficients(mtoy)[1]
names(mtoy_i) <- NULL
mtoy_b <- coefficients(mtoy)[2]
names(mtoy_b) <- NULL
mtoy_cp <- coefficients(mtoy)[3]
names(mtoy_cp) <- NULL
  • Poisson regression
    • \(b \times e^{(i + bM + c'X)}\) = \(0.261 \times e^{(0.255 + 0.261 M + 0.839 X)}\)

Conditional indirect effect

  • The indirect effect is the product of the two values
  • In this case, it is:
    • \(a \times b \times e^{(i + bM + c'X)}\) = \(-0.119 \times 0.261 \times e^{(0.255 + 0.261 M + 0.839 X)}\)
  • Note that it is conditional on both \(X\) and \(M\)
    • Letâs break that down some
  • Start with the \(X\) values: 0 and 1
x <- c(0, 1)
  • What are the predicted \(M\) values for each of those \(X\) values?
    • Use the equation \(\hat{M} = i_{MX} + aX\)
m <- xtom_i + xtom_a * x
  • Now we have \(X\) values and their corresponding \(M\) values
  • I added the \(X\) and \(M\) values, as well as all of the various coefficient values, to a data frame so we can calculate things
med_pred <- data.frame(x, m, xtom_i, xtom_a, mtoy_i, mtoy_b, mtoy_cp)
  • Calculate the indirect effect for each set of values
med_pred$ind <- xtom_a * mtoy_b * exp(mtoy_i + mtoy_b * m + mtoy_cp * x)
med_pred
  x        m   xtom_i    xtom_a   mtoy_i    mtoy_b   mtoy_cp         ind
1 0 1.242024 1.242024 -0.118866 0.254552 0.2608472 0.8394682 -0.05529634
2 1 1.123158 1.242024 -0.118866 0.254552 0.2608472 0.8394682 -0.12411010
  • Too many things in this table
    • Letâs just print the columns we care about: \(X\), \(M\), indirect effect
round(med_pred[c(1:2, 8)], 3)
  x     m    ind
1 0 1.242 -0.055
2 1 1.123 -0.124
  • Conditional indirect effects
    • For women, the indirect effect of gender to sensation to number of drinks is -0.055
    • For men, the indirect effect of gender to sensation to number of drinks is -0.124
  • Compare to the ânaiveâ indirect effect that ignores nonlinear effects
    • \(a \times b = -0.119 \times 0.261 = -0.031\)

Bootstrapping indirect effect

  • This is just one way to bootstrap

  • EDIT: I forgot to get separate estimates for each gender

    • The whole point of the conditional effects hereâ¦
    • The original estimate made no sense because there was one CI for two different estimates
    • There was also a really dumb typo in the formula that was messing things up
abexpib1_jpa <- function(data, indices) {
    val <- data[indices,] 
    fit1 <- lm(sensation4 ~ gender, data = val)
    fit2 <- glm(y ~ sensation + gender, 
                family = poisson(link = "log"), 
                data = val)
    xtom_b0 <- coefficients(fit1)[1]
    xtom_b1 <- coefficients(fit1)[2]
    mtoy_b0 <- coefficients(fit2)[1]
    mtoy_b1 <- coefficients(fit2)[2]
    mtoy_b2 <- coefficients(fit2)[3]
    x <- c(0,1)
    m <- xtom_b0 + xtom_b1 * x
    indirect <- xtom_a * mtoy_b * exp(mtoy_i + mtoy_b * m + mtoy_cp * x)
    return(indirect)
} 

output <- boot(data = jpa, 
               statistic = abexpib1_jpa, 
               R = 1000)
